definition.value: Identification with a profession, exhibited by an aligning of roles, responsibilities, values, and ethical standards as accepted by the profession.

A religious identity is the set of beliefs and practices generally held by an individual, involving adherence to codified beliefs and rituals and study of ancestral or cultural traditions, writings, history, and mythology, as well as faith and mystic experience.
The identity formed by integration of one's life experiences into an internalized, evolving story of the self that provides the individual with a sense of unity and purpose in life.
A numerical identifier.

A number used by the governments of many countries as a means of tracking their citizens, permanent residents, and temporary residents for the purposes of work, taxation, government benefits, health care, and other governmentally-related functions.
A numeric password used in the process of authenticating a user accessing a system.

A form of argument that attempts to establish a claim by showing that the opposite scenario would lead to absurdity or contradiction. It can be used to disprove a statement by showing that it would inevitably lead to a ridiculous, absurd, or impractical conclusion, or to prove a statement by showing that if it were false, then the result would be absurd or impossible.
Erroneously attempting to make a reasonable argument into an absurd one, by taking the argument to the extremes.

An appeal to extremes which compares gender and sexual minorities to someone who self-identifies as an attack helicopter. It falsely focuses upon self-identification rather than psychological and biological aspects of identity, insinuates that LGBTQIA+ persons are delusional in their identities, and compares requests for basic human rights to the ability to commit homicide.
The act of deceiving or the fact of being deceived.
The act of pretending to have beliefs, opinions, virtues, feelings, qualities, or standards that one does not actually have.

Sexual suggestiveness is visual, verbal, written or behavioral material or action with sexual undertones implying sexual intent in order to provoke sexual arousal. There are variations in the perception and display of sexual suggestiveness, including but not limited to gender, culture and generation.

A social and sexual behavior involving spoken or written communication, as well as body language, by one person to another, either to suggest interest in a deeper relationship with the other person, or if done playfully, for amusement.
Nightclub-like establishments which attracted feminine clientele (gay men and drag queens, and transgender women, as we would contemporarily refer to them).
A concise, terse, laconic, and/or memorable expression of a general truth or principle.

A concise, memorable, and usually philosophical aphorism that communicates an important truth derived from experience, custom, or both, and that many people consider true and credible because of its longeval tradition, i.e. being handed down generation to generation, or memetic replication.
The sequence of nucleotide residues along an RNA or DNA chain.
The sequence of nucleotide residues along a DNA chain.
The sequence of nucleotide residues along an RNA chain.
A protein acid sequence is the character representation of the molecular structure of a protein.
Groups that advocate for civil liberties.
Groups that advocate for civil rights.
A group that advocates for intersex persons.
A defined grouping of transfeminine persons, organizations, and subcultures, united by a common culture and social movements.
A defined grouping of transmasculine persons, organizations, and subcultures, united by a common culture and social movements.
A defined grouping of nonbinary persons, organizations, and subcultures, united by a common culture and social movements.
A defined grouping of transgender lesbians, organizations, and subcultures, united by a common culture and social movements.
A community of persons, typically of African descent, classed based on the social construction of race primarily prevalent in Europe and the Americas.

A community of persons who belong to an ethnic group of Americans with total or partial ancestry from any of the Black racial groups of Africa. The phrase generally refers to descendants of enslaved Black people who are from the United States.
Any of various communities of Afro-American LGBTQIA+ persons.
Any of various communities of Black LGBTQIA+ persons.
A usually urban geographic location with generally recognized boundaries wherein a relatively large number of LGBTQIA+ persons might live and work.
Gay villages are almost always mostly gay male areas, and are therefore classed as a subclass of gay male community. However, this is not always the case.
Any of various cultures of Indigenous peoples.
Any of various LGBTQIA+ subcultures specific to Indigenous peoples.

Although many Indigenous traditions and identities (such as Two-Spirit persons) existed before LGBTQ identifications, they are often grouped as such both by LGBTQ organizations and by those persons identifying as such. However, there may be important distinctions between modern conceptualizations and those of Indigenous persons.
Any of various LGBTQIA+ subcultures specific to American Indian peoples.
Any of various LGBTQIA+ subcultures specific to First Nations peoples of Canada.
Any of various LGBTQIA+ subcultures specific to Native Hawaiian peoples.
The culture of a particular nation or state.
A set of the practices, beliefs, and objects that are dominant or prevalent in a society at a given point in time.
A family where at least one parent has children that are not genetically related to the other spouse or partner.
Adoption wherein a parent does not meet the child before adopting.
A form of adoption in which the biological and adoptive families have access to varying degrees of each other's personal information and have an option of contact.
Families having members who belong to any of various sexual minorities.
Families having members who belong to any of various gender and/or sexual minorities.
Families having members who belong to any of various gender minorities.
Parents with LGBTQIA+ identities.
Parents who are of the same sex or gender.
Parents who are of different genders.
Parents who are gay men.
Parents who are lesbians.
